<isis lang="en">
    <stitle>DT-466E and 530E Diesel Engine Service (1995 through 1999) - SECTION 6: CONNECTING RODS, PISTONS, RINGS AND
        SLEEVES - PISTON AND ROD ASSEMBLY
    </stitle>
    <svcman/>
    <svcsubsec>
        <title>PISTON AND ROD ASSEMBLY</title>
        <svcproc svcproctype="remove" graphiccount="4">
            <title>REMOVAL</title>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>THE CARBON RIDGE MUST BE REMOVED BEFORE REMOVING THE PISTON AND ROD ASSEMBLY. THIS REDUCES THE
                        CHANCE OF PISTON RING LAND DAMAGE DURING REMOVAL.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Using a razor knife, scrape the carbon ridge from the top of the cylinder sleeve.</para>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>
                            <emph type="underscr">BE SURE</emph>
                            TO MARK EACH CONNECTING ROD CAP AND REASSEMBLE TO THE PERSPECTIVE CONNECTING ROD UPON
                            REMOVAL. ALSO MARK THE LOCATION OF THE CONNECTING ROD WITHIN THE CRANKCASE.
                        </para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Loosen the connecting rod bolts using a socket and breaker-bar (
                    <emph type="bold">Figure
                        <hotlnk xrefid="ef1600602">6.2</hotlnk>
                    </emph>
                    ).
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the bolts by hand.</para>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>The bolts should turn out of the connecting rod freely. If binding exists, check thread
                            condition carefully.
                        </para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the connecting rod cap and bearing insert. Refer to
                    <emph type="bold">Figure
                        <hotlnk xrefid="ef1600603">6.3</hotlnk>
                    </emph>
                    ).
                </para>
                <figure id="ef1600602" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="eg6901" filename="../figeg6/EG6901.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 6.2 Removing Connecting Rods Mounting Bolts</caption>
                </figure>
                <figure id="ef1600603" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="eg5909" filename="../figeg5/EG5909.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 6.3 Remove Connecting Rod Main Bearing Cap</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the piston and connecting rod assemblies as follows:</para>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Rotate the engine in a vertical position, front end up.</para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Push the piston and rod assembly from the cylinder bore using a wood or plastic
                        handle. Refer to
                        <emph type="bold">Figure
                            <hotlnk xrefid="ef1600604">6.4</hotlnk>
                        </emph>
                        .
                    </para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Once the piston rings are free of the cylinder bore, the assembly can be removed
                        from the top of the crankcase. Refer to
                        <emph type="bold">Figure
                            <hotlnk xrefid="ef1600605">6.5</hotlnk>
                        </emph>
                        .
                    </para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Match connecting rod and piston assemblies upon removal so they can be reinstalled
                        in their respective cylinder bores.
                    </para>
                    <figure id="ef1600604" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="eg6903" filename="../figeg6/EG6903.webp" type="webp"/>
                        <caption>Figure 6.4 Pushing Piston And Connecting Rod Assembly Thru Crankcase</caption>
                    </figure>
                    <figure id="ef1600605" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="eg5335" filename="../figeg5/EG5335.webp" type="webp"/>
                        <caption>Figure 6.5 Remove Piston And Connecting Rod Assembly</caption>
                    </figure>
                </step2>
            </step1>
        </svcproc>
    </svcsubsec>
